node.text: I love getting pics like this, from a patrol sergeant in a VERY busy and tough section of a town, using ASP badge cam videos at roll call as shift training for their officers. This particular one was difficult to make as it was a bad outcome, but those can be very good for learning too. This is a big motivation for doing the badge cams, alongside educating the general public about the difficult work our LEO do every day and with great professionalism for the vast, vast majority of their interactions. AFAIK right now there are about 20 law enforcement academies, about 200 patrol sergeants, 2 state POST boards, and one national POST board who use these videos to train officers. That is very gratifying!

node.text: I know this will be controversial to someC but the reason we have blue guns is to be able to use them in ways we couldn’t use a real gun safely. Pointing a blue gun at someone is no big deal, and while I think we should not be flippant or careless with blue guns I think that beyond very new shooters we can and should treat them differently. Here @redhawk_firearm_training is working with an instructor in our instructor certification program on coaching methods.

node.text:
"Shotguns are hard to shoot well, and recoil sucks!" I disagree.

Here, a young girl who is 4'11", 84 lbs shoots a 12ga short-barreled shotgun with full power loads. Proper push-pull technique makes the shotgun a different animal entirely.

This young woman is the daughter of @battlecomp owner and Mythbuster-famous industry icon Alan Normandy.

node.text:
Reposted from my friend, LtCol(ret) Freddie Blish who knows a thing or two, because he's seen a thing or two. Learn from his wisdom.

"A fellow who shoots a lot of AR’s likes to put his support arm way out on the barrel when shooting. It’s the best way to operate it he says. Depending on the method it does help drive the gun from target/threat to target/threat more efficiently. But he needed to remember not to do that when he transitioned to his AR pistol. He didn’t shoot himself, this was damage to the finger from being next to the compensator when he pulled the trigger.

I know a Force Recon Corpsman who did something similar with an SBR that had a muzzle brake, except it was his support side thumb. He held his hand too far out on the rail with thumb forward next to the brake. The gas from the brake evaporated the tip of his thumb forward of the knuckle.

I watch for those kinds of potential disasters when training shooters at Gunsite carbine classes. We’ll probably see some of that in the Vets 223 next week. That and lots of muzzle brakes because of the “punishing recoil” of the .223 cartridge… Actually it is from too many of them seeing the “cool kids” using them or promoting them, “gotta be like Mike!”

Placing your hand near the gas port of a piston carbine can cause serious burns as well. Had a student in a 223 class that I warned using a LWRC with the “cool kids” C Clamp hold with his support hand directly over the piston gas port. He reverted to that style during some drills and thankfully was wearing gloves. He learned a valuable lesson with just minor damage to his glove and not his hands."

node.text: Important self-defense lesson here!! This poor little cottontail was minding his own business until my son’s Murder Cat chased him. He ran like heck and jumped in my pool to get away and kept his little snoot above water. I saw it happen and put MC inside and fished him out of the pool. He sat here awhile and then hopped off to resume his bunny life. Big lesson: don’t give up! Fight for your life even if you’re outmatched. You might just make it. :)
